volume.name: Ray Bradbury Comics: Tales of Terror

deck: A Topps Comics anthology in collaboration with legendary science fiction author Ray Bradbury.
description:
Content

Ray Bradbury Comics: The Illustrated Man # 1, published by Topps Comics, features stories based upon the fiction of author Ray Bradbury. These include "The Illustrated Man," adapted by Guy Davis; "The Visitor," with script and breakdown art by P. Craig Russel and finished art by Michael Lark, and "Zero Hour," adapted be the late Jack Kamen. The issue also features an introduction by Bradbury himself, as well as a one-page pin-up by Tim Bradstreet. The anthology is a one-shot.

Credits

Aside from the credits below, colors were provided by Julia Koch for "The Illustrated Man," and with Michael Lark for "The Visitor," as well as by Rodney Dunn for "Zero Hour."

"Zero Hour" was originally presented in Planet Stories (1947), and reprinted in 1953's Weird Fantasy #18, published by EC Comics.

description:
After his existential thriller (Why Are You Doing This?), his Parisian famous-writers crime caper (The Left Bank Gang), and his time-travel story (I Killed Adolf Hitler), Jason's fourth full-color album may feature his loopiest premise yet. Set in the present time, The Last Musketeer stars the by-now centuries old musketeer Athos, who has been reduced to a suavely dressed but useless near-panhandler trading on his now almost extinct fame. All this changes when one day the Martians attack Earth. Suddenly there is a need for swashes to be buckled, and Athos leaps back into the fray with a vengeance. The Last Musketeer is a vintage sci-fi adventure with a unique twist from an internationally acclaimed cartoonist.

Jason's fourth full-color album may feature his loopiest premise yet.

The acclaimed graphic novelist Jason returns with his most eagerly awaited book yet, thanks to the inclusion of the title story, the world’s first (and likely last) chess western, originally serialized in 2008 in the New York Times Sunday Magazine “Funny Pages” section.

This 216-page hardcover book features five yarns — all brand new with the exception of the aforementioned “Low Moon,” which is collected into book form for the first time.

The new stories lead off with “Emily Says Hello,” a typically deadpan Jason tale of murder, revenge and sexual domination. Then, the wordless “&” tells two tales at once: one about a skinny guy trying to steal enough money to save his ill mother, and the other about a fat guy murderously trying to woo his true love. The reason we follow these two parallel stories becomes obvious only on the very last page, in Jason’s inimitable genre-mashing style.

Entirely told in pantomime, this suite of short tales veers from the funny to the terrifying, to the surreal to the touching. Jason's clean, deadpan style features animal-headed characters with mask-like faces that hide a wealth of emotion and complexity, leavened with wicked wit.
name: Sshhhh!

description: From a surrealistic trip into the mind of the Mask to a sweaty S&M club, the trail leads Marshal Law to an Earth shaking battle with his most hated foe -- the man who killed his girlfriend ten years ago. The creators of Marshal Law pit two of comics' most maniacal characters in a hilariously violent face-off.

Vesta colony, 2063 AD. They thought they were alone. They were wrong. Earth is preparing to send colonists to the Tellus colony next. Kalen Selina is part of the Tellus group. Nathan West, her boyfriend, was dropped at the last minute, so he joins the military to get into space.

1. "No Title" (Dracula and Zorro) written by Don McGregor, penciled by Tom Yeates and inked by Rick Magyar and lettered by John Costanza. Reprinted from Dracula Versus Zorro #1.
  2. "Command Decision" A TeenAgents Prologue (TeenAgents) written by Kurt Busiek, penciled by Neil Vokes, inked by John Beatty and lettered by Richard Starkings and John Gaushell.
  3. "Citizen's Arrest" (Silver Star) written by Kurt Busiek, penciled by James W. Fry, inked by Terry Austin and lettered by Chris Eliopoulos.
  4. "No Title" (Bill the Galactic Hero) written by Howard Zimmerman, penciled and inked by Mike Gustovich and lettered by Unknown.

Notes:

  • An all black and white issue.
  • There is a second printing of this issue.
  • Cover credits are D.A. and Yeates (Unknown? Dan Adkins?).

description: 'You have your fear, which might become reality. And you have Godzilla, which IS reality.' - From Godzilla, King of the Monsters (1956). And what a reality it was! For two years, Japan's greatest export was one of Marvel's biggest stars, and the King of the Monsters upheld his title against some of the best and worst the House of Ideas had to offer - including the Fantastic Four, the Avengers, and Fury and the Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.! Godzilla shrinks, goes West, travels through time to battle Devil Dinosaur, and hosts one of Spider-Man's most gratuitous guest-shots ever! Plus: aliens, mutants, mad and almost a dozen MORE giant monsters! It's so big, you can't miss it!
name: King of the Monsters!

description: Though this issue marks the changeover from the David Tennant tenth Doctor to Matt Smith's eleventh Doctor in the comic strip, coinciding with Smith's first full episode airing on BBC 1, neither the Doctor nor his new companion Amy Pond appear in this issue's strip, which is the first half of a two part story, Attack of the Space Leeches. Instead, the strip focuses on a bystander, Stephen, who witnesses the titular attack and is fleeing from the aliens in search of help; the TARDIS materialises on the last page, with the Doctor and Amy inside but unseen till next issue.

description: Part of the angelic bureaucracy, Karasu is sent to earth to retrieve a demon living among humans. However, he's surprised to discover that Shirasagi only wants to throw away his heritage and his powers, and live as a human, and a holy human at that. A priest working out of a bar in the city, Shirasagi teaches children and is generally an all-around wonderful person. But Heaven and Hell both want him back and it's going to be quite a battle.
name: Vol. 1

description: Karasu may have retrieved Shirasagi from the clutches of Beelzebub once, but Hell isn't quite ready to give up its claim just yet. However, the appearance of Koumori and Sarugami--a new ally and an old friend--may force our pair to not only acknowledge their debt to each other, but their true feelings as well.
name: Vol. 2

description: Koumori leads Karasu and Shirasagi through the wastes of Purgatory, while high above, the Seraphim argue over how best to prevent the Distortion from spreading any further. When the war between Heaven and Hell begins once again, Dominions and Karasu restart their own fight, but soon the Archduke gets involved, and what happens in the end will take everyone by surprise! Faith, passion and betrayal collide as the universe spirals downward towards chaos... But are the feelings of two star-crossed lovers enough to set things right?
name: Vol. 3

description: Someone has assembled a group of high school girls--rumored to be witche --and dropped them off in the woods. Among them is Makoto, a private eye with an uncanny, almost otherworldly, ability to get the bad guy. But one by one, the witches die a violent death--can Makoto use his sixth sense to prevent bloody carnage from overflowing?!
name: Vol. 1

description: Makoto, the uncanny super-sleuth who was sent on an ill-fated witch hunt, is not everything he seems to be--and a hidden dark side might manifest itself in the most wicked of ways as he and the girls try to find their way to safety. When he reunites with the mysteriously invincible Mahiro, she finds that she may have feelings for Makoto. Meanwhile, Rinko encounters a mysterious hooded man who is a student of the dark arts...and has come to teach someone a horrific lesson in forgiveness.
name: Vol. 2
